<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<introduction component="profesor" xml:id="gra3-uni5-secC-intro" xml:lang="es-ES" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<objectives>
  <ul>
    <li><p>[++++++++++++++++]</p></li>
    <li>Explain equivalence of fractions in special cases and express whole numbers as fractions and fractions as whole numbers.</li>
  </ul>
</objectives>  
<p>[++++++++++++++++]</p>  
<p>
  In this section, students learn that equivalent fractions are fractions that are the same size.
</p>
<sbsgroup widths="60% 35%" margins="0% 5%">
  <sidebyside>
    <p>
      They first identify equivalent fractions by noticing parts that are of equal length on fraction strips and tape diagrams.
    </p>
    <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-170373">
      <shortdescription>cinta dividida en 3 partes iguales, con una parte sombreada.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </sidebyside>
  <sidebyside>
    <p>
      For example, the shaded third in the first diagram is the same size as the two shaded sixths in the second diagram, so <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{2}{6}</m> are equivalent.
    </p>
    <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-170374">
      <shortdescription>cinta dividida en 6 partes iguales, con dos partes sombreadas.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </sidebyside>
</sbsgroup>
<p>
  Students see that they can show equivalence by decomposing each fractional part into smaller parts, or by grouping fractional parts to make larger parts.
</p>
<sbsgroup widths="60% 35%" margins="0% 5%">
  <sidebyside>
    <p>
      Suppose we want to show that the shaded parts of this diagram represent both <m>\frac{6}{8}</m> and <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>.
    </p>
    <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-170383">
      <shortdescription>cinta dividida en 8 partes iguales, con seis partes sombreadas.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </sidebyside>
  <sidebyside>
    <p>
      If we group 2 eighths together, we have 4 equal groups, each being a fourth. We can see that the 6 shaded eighths and 3 shaded fourths are the same size.
    </p>
    <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-170382">
      <shortdescription>cinta dividida en 4 partes iguales, cada parte conteniendo 2 octavos, con tres partes sombreadas.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </sidebyside>
</sbsgroup>
<p>
  Later, students learn that equivalent fractions are the same distance away from 0 and are therefore located at the same point on the number line. They write equations to express equivalence, including for fractions that are equivalent to whole numbers.
</p>
<image source="svg-source/tikz-file-147451">
  <shortdescription>recta numérica de 0 a 1, con 7 divisiones, cada una marcada con el octavo correspondiente por arriba, y por debajo con el cuarto correspondiente.</shortdescription>
</image>
<p>
  <md>
    \frac{6}{8} = \frac{3}{4}
  </md>  
</p>
</introduction>
